data.content:
This is the **C# 14 `Span<T>` overload resolution change**.

## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions make `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this Span<T>, T)` a better overload match than `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` when called on an array. Since `MemoryExtensions.Contains` is a **span-based method**, it **cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree**, so the compiler (or interpreter) throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the call to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<T>`:

```csharp
// Before (breaks in .NET 10)
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.Contains(num);

// After — cast to IEnumerable<int> to select Enumerable.Contains
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);
// or:
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
// or call the static method explicitly:
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three options ensure the compiler picks the `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which is representable in expression trees.
